acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Collection was deposited at RAC by Asia Society, December 1977 and officially donated to RAC in 2016.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Asia Society was founded in 1956 by John D. Rockefeller 3rd to promote greater knowledge and understanding of Asia in the United States, and to strengthen the relationship between Americans and Asians through international cultural exchange. The Asia Society has grown to become a global institution with an educational mandate and cross-disciplinary programming.

The Asia Society headquarters are located in New York, and the Society maintains additional U.S. offices in California (Los Angeles and San Francisco), Texas (Houston) and Washington, D.C. and global centers in Australia (Melbourne), China (Shanghai), Hong Kong, India (Mumbai), South Korea (Seoul), and the Philippines (Manila).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: All records in the collection have been received from the Asia Society New York office, and document the activities of the Society through the New York office from inception in 1956 though the 1990s. Records documenting the activities of regional offices including those in Houston, Los Angeles and Washington, D.C. are minimal.
Records include: Correspondence, reports, administrative records, meetings, studies and seminar files, officer's files, department and program records, development and fundraising files.

The early activities of the Society are particularly well documented including the Southeast Asia Development Advisory Group (SEADAG) and Country Council records including but not limited to those of the China Council and and the India Council.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

odd.head: General

Inferior sound may be attributed to the original recording equipment, poor recording environment, or the subject speaking too far from the recording device. Efforts have been made to improve sound quality when possible. Recordings with poor sound quality have been identified in the items' note field.

physdesc.extent: Tassilo Adam film collection encompasses approximately 25,000 feet of film on 64 reels.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Tassilo Adam (1878-1955) was a German-born ethnographer who was appointed the official Ethnologist of the Dutch East Indies by the Governor General of Java. He was a photographer and amateur filmmaker with an anthropological and documentary approach to the Indonesian culture he captured on film. From 1929-1955, Adam was the curator of Oriental Art at the Brooklyn Museum.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Tassilo Adam film collection encompasses approximately 25,000 feet of film on 64 reels. The collection includes dupe negatives and prints in 16mm and 35mm formats.

Many reels contain duplicate content with varying image quality. Java Reels 1-11 contain superior image quality, as they are believed to have been copied straight from the nitrate original. Other reels are duplicates several generations away from original source. Many are believed to have been edited by Adam for presentational purposes.

The documentary footage was shot in Indonesia from 1921-1928 of dances, shadow play, dramatic dance, religious processions, wedding festivals in the palaces, and other ceremonies as well as dance finery, costumes of the Javanese nobles, everyday wear and dance attire. The bulk of the collection is of Central Java, comprising of court ceremonies and dances at the palaces of Jogyakarta and Surakarta, as well as village performances and rituals in the surrounding area.
Highlights of the collection include the films that capture
• Wayang Wong, a type of classical Javanese dance theatrical performance with themes taken from episodes of the Ramayana or Mahabharata
• Wayang Topeng, a Javanese theatrical performance in which performers wear masks.
• Kuda Kepang or Kuda Lumping, a traditional Javanese dance depicting a group of horsemen.

• Serimpi, a classical dance of Cental Java associated with royal palaces of Yogyakarta and Surakarta. The dance epitomizes the character of the royal court, and the dance became an important symbol of the ruler's power as well as the refinement of Javanese culture.

• Bedoyo dances, is a ritualized dance of Java and is associated with the royal palaces of Yogyakarta and Surakarta. The dance epitomizes the character of the royal court, and the dance became an important symbol of the ruler's power.
• Wayang Kulit, a Javanese shadow puppet theatrical performance
• Gamelan, a traditional orchestra of Java and Bali in Indonesia, made up predominantly of percussive instruments.
